#################################
# Introducing 
# TEA TEMPLATE #Expressions# v2
#--------------------------------
Which would allow us to write complex expressions 
that can resolve to terminal value expressions
in a RECURSIVE manner similar to variable substitution
in some higher-level programming language 
templating systems. 
#################################

# given variables
V:a:1
V:b:3
V:d:{TEA-TEMPLATE Expression}

# given a template expressions..
V:EXPR:{(#a#+#b#)*(#a#-#b#)}
V:EXPR2:{Expression in EXPR equivalent to #EXPR# is a #d#}

# re-write the specified expression (injects found variables/vaults at two levels)
R*!@:EXPR2

#which should produce:
#Expression in EXPR equivalent to (1+3)*(1-3) is a TEA-TEMPLATE Expression

# we also could just reduce/rewrite a template expression to a value...
R*!@:EXPR | R.:

#which should produce:
#(#a#+#b#)*(#a#-#b#) -> (1+3)*(1-3) -> 4*-2 -> -8

# We could also have just written..
R!@:{(#a#+#b#)*(#a#-#b#)} | R.: 
#should return "-8"

### EXAMPLE 2: Golden Ratio
v:vEXPR:{The Golden Ratio is computed as: ##vInnerVALUE##}
v:a:2
v:b:{(1/#a#)}
v:innerEXPR:{(1/#a#)*(1+5**#b#)}
r*!@:innerEXPR | r.: | v:vInnerVALUE
r*!@:vEXPR

## EXAMPLE 3: Recursive Vs Non-Recursive Resolution
# TESTING Recursive Template Resolution
V:a:1
V:b:{(1/#a#)}
V:c:{[#b# in c]} 
V:EXPR:{#a# + #b# + #c#}
v:MSG:{I read the expression about #a# as:
 #EXPR#
and then as 
##EXPR## and #c# as ##c##
}
y:MSG | R@:

# returns:
I read the expression about 1 as:
 #a# + #b# + #c#
and then as 
1 + (1/1) + [(1/1) in c] and [#b# in c] as [(1/1) in c]

# while...
y:MSG | R!@:

# returns:
I read the expression about 1 as:
 1 + (1/1) + [(1/1) in c]
and then as 
1 + (1/1) + [(1/1) in c] and [(1/1) in c] as [(1/1) in c]